    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3408291467" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3408291467" />
    <a title="George" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/107938824-george"><img alt="George" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577959938p2/107938824.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3408291467?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="George" class="user" itemprop="url" name="George" href="/user/show/107938824-george">George</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789380118291" href="/book/show/30253249-reform-or-revolution">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3408291467" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7996366874429427065">I think this book has a few peculiar aspects that potentially count as weaknesses; although it is a classic and useful introduction to the problems of reformism, I don&apos;t think it is Luxemburg&apos;s best work. I say this because <i> Reform or Revolution </i> does at times read oddly like a sustained review of Eduard Bernstein&apos;s <i> Preconditions of Socialism. </i> I think Luxemburg mentions him in every chapter and his name is even in the last sentence of the work, which, if not necessarily bad, has the effect of </span>
  <span id="freeText7996366874429427065" style="display:none">I think this book has a few peculiar aspects that potentially count as weaknesses; although it is a classic and useful introduction to the problems of reformism, I don't think it is Luxemburg's best work. I say this because <i> Reform or Revolution </i> does at times read oddly like a sustained review of Eduard Bernstein's <i> Preconditions of Socialism. </i> I think Luxemburg mentions him in every chapter and his name is even in the last sentence of the work, which, if not necessarily bad, has the effect of dating the book in a peculiar way and undermining its otherwise timeless relevance.<br /><br />In the first paragraph of the introduction Luxemburg insists on nuance: "Between social reforms and revolution there exists for the Social Democracy an indissoluble tie. The struggle for reforms is its means; the social revolution, its aim." It's important to keep this in mind throughout because from this point on Luxemburg tends to attack reformism pretty insistently. For example, in Chapter 7, trade unions and cooperatives represent only "an attack made on the twigs of the capitalist tree." In Chapter 8, "Legislative reform and revolution are different factors in the development of class society. They condition and complement each other, and are at the same time reciprocally exclusive, as are the north and south poles, the bourgeoisie and proletariat." I think these claims are fair and accurate, but you could conceivably read them as denials of the value of unions and legislative reform, which does not seem to be Luxemburg's real point, as is clear from the introduction. This is also another problem associated with how close the book sticks to Bernstein: for Luxemburg, the influence of Bernstein's fundamentally unscientific and anti-Marxist views, his reformist attack on the possibility of revolution, was likely a pernicious problem that she sought to counteract, hence the strength of her polemic against reformism in the body of the book.<br /><br />Of course, I say this, but reformism, liberal and otherwise, remains pernicious to this day, so perhaps I go too far in criticising Luxemburg for polemic. Another potential weakness of the book with a similar structure is the question of economic dogmatism or determinism. It seems at time that Luxemburg has an impressive degree of faith in the necessary collapse of capitalism, which is sometimes something difficult to accept at face value for contemporary Marxists, given the resilience which capitalism as a system seems to have shown to the destructive potential of its own crises. She insists in the first chapter that "the scientific basis of socialism rests, as is well known, on three principal results of capitalist development," which are the growing anarchy of capitalist activity, which leads "inevitably to ruin;" the socialisation of some parts of the economy; and increasing class consciousness. On the one hand, Luxemburg confidently uses words like "inevitable" to the extent that you might criticise her for believing uncritically in revolution, which goes hand in hand with worrying that she attacks reformism too eagerly. On the other hand, her scientific account here also demands the growth of genuine class consciousness: if we read attentively, we can see that while Luxemburg does see revolution as inevitable, she is clear that this is only in the event that proletarian class consciousness arises, and while class consciousness grows just as the rate of profit falls (i.e. as a necessary result of capitalist development, concentration, and extraction) it is arguably a much more complex type of growth, frequently susceptible to a range of capitalist interventions, ideological and material, that don't apply to, say, the continuously increasing concentration of capital. In other words, Luxemburg is not deferring all Marxist praxis to the rapturous moment of revolution, despite what a cursory reading might indicate. <br /><br />This nuance is potentially a peculiar weakness of the book because many of her arguments are widely spaced across the (admittedly not very long) text, and quoting them out of context could be misleading. Ironically this is perhaps a example of the importance of "the axis of intellectual crystallisation around which isolated facts group themselves in the organic whole of a coherent conception," which is a nice expression Luxemburg uses to denote the scientific Marxism of which Bernstein is incapable, in Chapter 9.<br /><br />These are the kinds of standard and sophomoric channels of reform/revolution debate that can be found in many corners of Twitter, but reading this book is a good way to cycle through them and line them up clearly. There are also some perhaps lesser-known interesting moments that I'd like to mention, however, which do not so often fall into these standard discussions.<br /><br />Luxemburg's discussion of credit is one of the things I found most interesting in this book. She points out that the credit system effectively serves to accelerate "the return of capital into production" by allowing capitalists to borrow the money of other capitalists (chapter 2). This ties in nicely to her later argument that Bernstein is wrong to point to the proliferation of shareholding societies as proof that capital is becoming more diffuse and less concentrated. Luxemburg is clear that a shareholding society with 10,000 members does not represent 10,000 different capitals, but one dense capital, which bears out the scientific Marxist prediction that capital is becoming more concentrated in order to try (and fail) to arrest a fall in the rate of profit (chapter 6). This theory of credit in fact attests to the same phenomenon: capital is literally concentrated in shareholding societies, but also 'fictitiously' concentrated among capitalists who, through financial mechanisms, are able to conjure up capital through credit. The particular problem of credit is that while it is well-suited to entering and accelerating production, it tends not to enter the process of exchange: "At the first symptom of the crisis, credit melts away. It abandons exchange where it would still be found indispensable, and appearing instead, ineffective and useless, there where some exchange still continues, it reduces to a minimum the consumption capacity of the market." Thus, as Luxemburg writes later, credit is both a remedy for falling profit and the illness itself (a <i> pharmakon, </i> you might say).<br /><br />This discussion of credit also gives rise to some evergreen comments on the role of state intervention in managing crisis. Luxemburg writes that credit "aggravates the antagonism existing between the social character of production and private capitalist ownership by rendering necessary the intervention of the state in production." And yet, the form this state intervention so often takes, including in the present historical moment, is the generation of credit: forgivable R&amp;D loans to businesses, demand-side stimulus loans for first-home buyers, and the issue of government bonds or quantitative easing. <br /><br />Luxemburg's theory of credit is one of the ways in which she expands and justifies the scientific inevitability of capitalism's collapse. She writes that "credit is far from being a means of capitalist adaptation. It is, on the contrary, a means of destruction of the most extreme revolutionary significance." Everything she says seems to be true, and in fact seems to be born out by the number of crises in recent decades that seem entirely linked to disasters of the credit system, such as the Asian debt crisis and the GFC. And yet! Capitalism is still here. I have a suspicion that the richest reading of Luxemburg's <i> Reform or Revolution </i> will be the one that sees the synthesis between her theory of credit and her discussions of militarism and agriculture. I think that if there is any theory of crisis that strikes the contemporary Marxist as plausible in the face of climate change, it will be the one that combines a critical optimism (Luxemburg's fundamental claim remains that the people of the earth who actually produce its material wealth must seize political power) with an increasingly accurate understanding of the flexibility of capitalism as a system and the inflexibility of the climate's tipping points.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7996366874429427065" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


