    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_962149563" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/962149563" />
    <a title="Itai Farhi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1067540-itai-farhi"><img alt="Itai Farhi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599951082p2/1067540.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/962149563?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Itai Farhi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Itai Farhi" href="/user/show/1067540-itai-farhi">Itai Farhi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1067540-itai-farhi?shelf=judaism">judaism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1067540-itai-farhi?shelf=leftist">leftist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1067540-itai-farhi?shelf=theoretical-formation">theoretical-formation</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer962149563" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer281397191072348363">Luxemburg&apos;s polemic against Bernstein&apos;s opportunistic eclecticism, by analyzing the motivations behind revisionism, remains current and overflowing with force. Of particular interest is her principled resistance to the politics of &quot;immediate &apos;practical&apos; results&quot; which can be overcome &quot;only with the help of the arms furnished us by Marx.&quot; Luxemburg&apos;s wit is sharp: the lemonade joke in Ch. 4 deserves to be included in studies of Jewish humor.</span>
  <span id="freeText281397191072348363" style="display:none">Luxemburg's polemic against Bernstein's opportunistic eclecticism, by analyzing the motivations behind revisionism, remains current and overflowing with force. Of particular interest is her principled resistance to the politics of "immediate 'practical' results" which can be overcome "only with the help of the arms furnished us by Marx." Luxemburg's wit is sharp: the lemonade joke in Ch. 4 deserves to be included in studies of Jewish humor.</span>
  <a data-text-id="281397191072348363" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


