<div id="review_3588967339" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3588967339" />
    <a title="Stefan Gugler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21258671-stefan-gugler"><img alt="Stefan Gugler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577458544p2/21258671.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3588967339?book_show_action=true">Nov 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stefan Gugler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stefan Gugler" href="/user/show/21258671-stefan-gugler">Stefan Gugler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3588967339" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5963403152473167671">I don&apos;t feel particularly revisionist, but ... *ducks-and-covers*<br/><br/>No, jokes aside, I really liked it. Luxemburg is such a feisty badass to read, it&apos;s a real joy to see how she takes down Bernstein.<br/><br/>I don&apos;t know enough about historical materialism to judge whether Luxemburg laid out the argument correctly but I assume it&apos;s good, because it&apos;s very well liked by big Marxist thinkers. When reading an argumentarium as R&amp;R in a way I&apos;d rather be more familiar with the opposing opinion to play devil&apos;s ad</span>
  <span id="freeText5963403152473167671" style="display:none">I don't feel particularly revisionist, but ... *ducks-and-covers*<br /><br />No, jokes aside, I really liked it. Luxemburg is such a feisty badass to read, it's a real joy to see how she takes down Bernstein.<br /><br />I don't know enough about historical materialism to judge whether Luxemburg laid out the argument correctly but I assume it's good, because it's very well liked by big Marxist thinkers. When reading an argumentarium as R&amp;R in a way I'd rather be more familiar with the opposing opinion to play devil's advocate, yet unfortunately, I haven't read Bernstein's work, so I can only offer some general observations:<br />Let's take an example of something that is definitely good that happened, e.g. voting for women. Women couldn't vote (at least in Switzerland) when Luxemburg was around. Now they can and I think it's definitely good. But in a certain framing, that would be deemed as liberal incrementalism. I agree in a way, that many things that the neoliberal paradigm of society offers us is just a mere distraction (e.g. corporate LGBT-rights, kneeling politicians) from revolution. On the other hand (a phrase about which L. made fun, ha!), it seems that there are in fact definitely good things that happened, as mentioned, women's suffrage. So to argue for revolution here is (if I'm not misrepresenting) tantamount to saying that the energy put into early feminism would rather have been spent for the revolutionary cause. In a way, maybe yes, if we'd live in a utopia now, this is true, but I feel it's very hard to counterfactually argue for that position and it becomes almost unfalsifiable.<br /><br />I feel 100 years ago, when L. wrote this piece, together with all the other Marxists around, I think it was just unexpected how recalcitrant capitalism turns out to be in the 21st century and how much capacity for absorbing ideology it might gain. I thin reviving L. today and provide her time to write maybe a 500 page R&amp;R Redux might be very useful and a bit more nuanced as per adaption to the material conditions that happened in the past 100 years.<br /><br />Again, generally, I think it was a great read and provides important insight in the thought of early 20th century Marxism, many of which is still up-to-date.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5963403152473167671" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

