  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3862479472" />
    <a title="JC" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8995319-jc"><img alt="JC" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1492785114p2/8995319.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3862479472?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JC" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JC" href="/user/show/8995319-jc">JC</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8995319-jc?shelf=communist">communist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8995319-jc?shelf=marxist">marxist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8995319-jc?shelf=revolt">revolt</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8995319-jc?shelf=jewish">jewish</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3862479472" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1603735766909574416">I’m actually not quite sure the first time I heard about Rosa Luxemburg. I suppose the first time I felt compelled to read her was after encountering Cornel West write about her in his book Prophesy Deliverance. I’ve since encountered <a href='https://www.marxists.org/archive/luxemburg/1905/misc/socialism-churches.htm' rel='nofollow noopener'>some interesting stuff Luxemburg wrote about Christianity, churches, and socialism</a>, particularly on the ‘communism of consumption’ of the early Christian church, but the absence of any ‘communism of production’. <br/><br/>This distinction between production and consumption a</span>
  <span id="freeText1603735766909574416" style="display:none">I’m actually not quite sure the first time I heard about Rosa Luxemburg. I suppose the first time I felt compelled to read her was after encountering Cornel West write about her in his book Prophesy Deliverance. I’ve since encountered <a href="https://www.marxists.org/archive/luxemburg/1905/misc/socialism-churches.htm" rel="nofollow noopener">some interesting stuff Luxemburg wrote about Christianity, churches, and socialism</a>, particularly on the ‘communism of consumption’ of the early Christian church, but the absence of any ‘communism of production’. <br /><br />This distinction between production and consumption arises in this text in a very fascinating way that brings to mind some issues that I’ve seen argued over within leftist discussions of socialism as it exists today. This is an excerpt of a critique (one of many) Luxemburg levels at Bernstein:<br /><br />“Bernstein’s socialism offers to the workers the prospect of sharing in the wealth of society. The poor are to become rich. How will this socialism be brought about? …Bernstein’s socialism is to be realised with the aid of these two instruments: labour unions – or as Bernstein himself characterises them, economic democracy – and co-operatives. The first will suppress industrial profit; the second will do away with commercial profit. <br /><br />Co-operatives – especially co-operatives in the field of production constitute a hybrid form in the midst of capitalism. They can be described as small units of socialised production within capitalist exchange. But in capitalist economy exchanges dominate production. As a result of competition, the complete domination of the process of production by the interests of capital – that is, pitiless exploitation – becomes a condition for the survival of each enterprise. The domination of capital over the process of production expresses itself in the following ways. Labour is intensified. The work day is lengthened or shortened, according to the situation of the market. And, depending on the requirements of the market, labour is either employed or thrown back into the street. In other words, use is made of all methods that enable an enterprise to stand up against its competitors in the market. The workers forming a co-operative in the field of production are thus faced with the contradictory necessity of governing themselves with the utmost absolutism. They are obliged to take toward themselves the role of capitalist entrepreneur – a contradiction that accounts for the usual failure of production co-operatives which either become pure capitalist enterprises or, if the workers’ interests continue to predominate, end by dissolving.”<br /><br />I find it fascinating that Luxemburg uses the phrase “the poor are to become rich” and elsewhere writing:<br /><br />“Co-operatives and trade unions are totally incapable of transforming the capitalist mode of production. This is really understood by Bernstein, though in a confused manner. For he refers to co-operatives and trade unions as a means of reducing the profit of the capitalists and thus enriching the workers. In this way, he renounces the struggle against the capitalist mode of production and attempts to direct the socialist movement to struggle against “capitalist distribution.” Again and again, Bernstein refers to socialism as an effort towards a “just, juster and still more just” mode of distribution.”<br /><br />You can find fascinating echoes of this revisionism in Deng Xiaoping’s notion of letting some people get rich first so that eventually everyone can become rich (i.e. ‘common prosperity). Yet Luxemburg acutely identifies that production is where the issue of un-freedom lies. The capitalist mode of production exists under the logics of capitalist competition. I recall the worker-owned co-operative café in Kingston, The Sleepless Goat, eventually close its doors. Not that it didn’t do amazing work for the time it was around, feeding poor and homeless people soup as well as providing community space for the wider Kingston community. But it could not sustain itself under a capitalist economy. As I heard Taiaiake Alfred say, the only way you win under capitalism is by being a good capitalist. And so Luxemburg correctly points out that co-operatives so often either become just another capitalist enterprise, or they ultimately dissolve.<br /><br />In so many ways, really-existing socialism operating in a world of capitalist hegemony ultimately was coerced into replicating some of the worst aspects of capitalism under the banner of socialism. In so many cases, workers had to produce under the unrelenting logics of capitalism – making more and more bricks with less and less straw as the Israelite slaves were forced to do under Pharaoh in Egypt (Exodus 5). This was also the case for the Soviet Union’s arms race with the U.S., where capitalism’s militarism became reflected in the largest ‘really existing’ socialist state on the planet. I’ve recently finished reading Italo Calvino’s “If on a winter’s night” and there’s this amazing chapter that very charmingly alludes to G.K. Chesterton’s “Man Who Was Thursday” which goes:<br /><br />“Once the process of falsification is set in motion, it won't stop. We're in a country where everything that can be falsified has been falsified: paintings in museums, gold ingots, bus tickets. The counterrevolution and the revolution fight with salvos of falsification: the result is that nobody can be sure what is true and what is false, the political police simulate revolutionary actions and the revolutionaries disguise themselves as policemen."<br />"And who gains by it, in the end?"<br />"It's too soon to say. We have to see who can best exploit the falsifications, their own and those of the others: whether it's the police or our organization.”<br /><br />One sometimes gets the sense that countries that fly the banner of socialism, but still live under the global hegemony of capitalist economy, are very aware that socialism is in competition with capitalism, yet to compete within realms of legitimacy, they sometimes replicate the atrocities of capitalism to generate the same illusions of prosperity and good governance that capitalism has so often tried to project in embarrassing exercises in optics (which is precisely the game of capitalist competition). I suppose what these really-existing socialist countries might claim is that they are doing this out of a sense of pragmatism. One cannot enact socialism overnight, one has to develop one’s productive forces, harness the dynamism of capitalism to create the abundance required for a future socialism. The issue that Luxemburg correctly points out is that these projects end up simply transforming into purely capitalist projects with the same exploitation and class relations, yet with an additional layer of authoritarian government (that was supposed to represent the masses, but must perpetuate the goals of sustaining production that has been set in motion).<br /><br />It is with a certain degree of irony that ardent defenders of Dengist reforms (on the left) accuse others of being ‘revisionists’. I don’t find it useful to call other people names, but I do think that certain forms of leftist apologetics for Deng can get a little too enthusiastic about harnessing capitalist production for socialist ends. Reformism is not simply social democrats in centrist parties trying to pressure their parties farther left. It also operates under the banner of ‘communist’ parties who pragmatically work with billionaires to trickle more wealth down to the proletariat, marching ever more slowly to some ‘common prosperity’.<br /><br />Yet Luxemburg also has some interesting remarks on the ‘revolution’ side of this equation, writing:<br /><br />“In the first place, it is impossible to imagine that a transformation as formidable as the passage from capitalist society to socialist society can be realised in one happy act. To consider that as possible is, again, to lend colour to conceptions that are clearly Blanquist. The socialist transformation supposes a long and stubborn struggle, in the course of which, it is quite probable the proletariat will be repulsed more than once so that for the first time, from the viewpoint of the final outcome of the struggle, it will have necessarily come to power “too early.””<br /><br />Luxemburg also makes careful distinctions between Blanquist coups and genuine revolutions with mass support:<br /><br />“In the first place, the seizure of political power by the proletariat, that is to say by a large popular class, is not produced artificially. It presupposes (with the exception of such cases as the Paris Commune, when the proletariat did not obtain power after a conscious struggle for its goal but fell into its hands like a good thing abandoned by everybody else) a definite degree of maturity of economic and political relations. Here we have the essential difference between coups d’etat along Blanqui’s conception which are accomplished by an “active minority” and burst out like pistol shot, always inopportunely, and the conquest of political power by a great conscious popular mass which can only be the product of the decomposition of bourgeois society and therefore bears in itself the economic and political legitimisation of its opportune appearance.”<br /><br />I also love reading Luxemburg’s takes on democracy in relation to socialism:<br /><br />“The fate of democracy is bound up, we have seen, with the fate of the labour movement. But does the development of democracy render superfluous or impossible a proletarian revolution, that is, the conquest of political power by the workers?<br /><br />…In the field of political relations, the development of democracy brings – in the measure that it finds a favourable soil – the participation of all popular strata in political life and, consequently, some sort of “people’s State.” But this participation takes the form of bourgeois parliamentarism, in which class antagonisms and class domination are not done away with, but are, on the contrary, displayed in the open. Exactly because capitalist development moves through these contradictions, it is necessary to extract the kernel of socialist society from its capitalist shell. Exactly for this reason must the proletariat seize political power and suppress completely the capitalist system. Of course, Bernstein draws other conclusions. If the development of democracy leads to the aggravation and not to the lessening of capitalist antagonisms, “the Social-Democracy,” he answers us, “in order not to render its task more difficult, must by all means try to stop social reforms and the extension of democratic institutions,”<br /><br />… If democracy has become superfluous or annoying to the bourgeoisie, it is on the contrary necessary and indispensable to the working class. It is necessary to the working class because it creates the political forms (autonomous administration, electoral rights, etc.) which will serve the proletariat as fulcrums in its task of transforming bourgeois society. Democracy is indispensable to the working class because only through the exercise of its democratic rights, in the struggle for democracy, can the proletariat become aware of its class interests and its historic task. In a word, democracy is indispensable not because it renders superfluous the conquest of political power by the proletariat but because it renders this conquest of power both necessary and possible.”<br /><br />I think Luxemburg emphasizes not only why democracy is important for workers, but that socialism is in many ways necessary for a properly functioning democracy. Because democracy is not the same thing as 'bourgeois parlimentarianism'. There are so many other things I want to comment on but lack the time. Luxemburg has this fantastic section on credit, and how that has in fact exacerbated capitalist instability and crises, and I think this has become ever more salient in the past few years, in various economic bubbles (e.g. the subprime mortgage crisis). While I disagree with Luxemburg's emphasis on the inevitability of socialism triumphing over capitalism because of its inevitable collapse, I do take that on as a matter of faith, rather than a scientific certainty. As Naomi Klein and the Invisible Committee have noted, capitalist theorists like Milton Friedman have basked in the notion of capitalist crises because it is the moment where Darwinian competition is most extreme and a moment of purification in which the most ruthless (or efficient by market demands) come out on top.<br /><br />I think so many leftist arguments revolve around issues of what means are justifiable to reach some agreed upon ends. The capitalist mode of production is a coercive one that extracts all it can out of labour, following Pharaoh’s dictate of more and more bricks with less and less straw. As I spend these days in Lent watching Passover and Easter approach, I think about what the radical Exodus event means today. One cannot enact liberation by going into the wilderness to only start making more and more bricks again with less and less straw. Of course liberation involves sacrifices. Arriving at the promised ‘another world’ requires disorienting wandering, and surviving on manna instead of the luscious cucumbers, melons, leeks, onions, and garlic grown along the Nile. But the property relations of Pharaoh were ones of slavery, not completely unlike the slave plantation labour on which modern capitalism relied upon in its own development. (See Jairus Banaji's observation in "Theory and History" that 'free' and 'unfree' labour are not in fact opposites.) Where the Exodus analogue must end however is where it reaches the conquest of Canaan. We cannot replicate the violence of Empire and commit genocide to build a utopia. We cannot displace and enact imperial violence to birth "another world" into existence.<br /><br />Another world is possible. Not only a world where the fruits of our labour are more evenly distributed, but another world where production unfolds differently. Not according to the ruthless dictate of capitalist competition (more bricks with less straw) but production that treats humans as humans. Humans are not commodities from which value is to be extracted. It is fitting Rosa Luxemburg’s birthday this year is during Lent. It’s a good time to ponder what our collective liberation will take.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1603735766909574416" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


