  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2452183421" />
    <a title="Grig O&#39;" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5998404-grig-o"><img alt="Grig O&#39;" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1313409440p2/5998404.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2452183421?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Grig O&#39;" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Grig O&#39;" href="/user/show/5998404-grig-o">Grig O&#39;</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2452183421" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10621035738445560368">A simultaneously glorious and tragic book. For all the prescience and eloquence of Rosa&apos;s critique of social democracy, the revolutionary alternative seems to be faring even worse. <br/><br/>Incremental improvements in the workers&apos; condition are reversible and subject to material (economic) conditions, and participation in bourgeois politics will always be constrained by these market-based realities. This reality, which Luxemburg captures so clearly, seems again and again to be ignored or concealed by fig</span>
  <span id="freeText10621035738445560368" style="display:none">A simultaneously glorious and tragic book. For all the prescience and eloquence of Rosa's critique of social democracy, the revolutionary alternative seems to be faring even worse. <br /><br />Incremental improvements in the workers' condition are reversible and subject to material (economic) conditions, and participation in bourgeois politics will always be constrained by these market-based realities. This reality, which Luxemburg captures so clearly, seems again and again to be ignored or concealed by figures all across the Left, who would rather keep pushing the Sisyphean rock of opportunism instead of taking a radical stance. And can we fault them, if that's the method that delivers results, as fleeting and partial as they may be?<br /><br />Indeed, that's the tragedy of our time (and also Rosa's, albeit to a lesser extent): for all of her scoffing at "utopian" (because non-scientific) incrementalism, and for all our advances in the past hundred years, humanity seems to be as far from the rational, humanist condition of radical internationalism as we've ever been.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10621035738445560368" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


