        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2006110188" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer259480037823087897">While there are some great owns of Bernstein and reformists in general (my favourite being Bernstein &quot;proposing to change the sea of capitalist bitterness into a sea of socialist sweetness, by progressively pouring into it bottles of social reformist lemonade&quot;), it struggles as a standalone text. Many of her economic arguments come off as mere assertions, and even though they are presumably backed up by some other Marxist texts there is little evidence of that within. <br/><br/>If you&apos;re just getting into</span>
  <span id="freeText259480037823087897" style="display:none">While there are some great owns of Bernstein and reformists in general (my favourite being Bernstein "proposing to change the sea of capitalist bitterness into a sea of socialist sweetness, by progressively pouring into it bottles of social reformist lemonade"), it struggles as a standalone text. Many of her economic arguments come off as mere assertions, and even though they are presumably backed up by some other Marxist texts there is little evidence of that within. <br /><br />If you're just getting into Marxism this isn't the place to start, but if you at least have a baseline of Marxist knowledge there is something for you here. Particularly Chapter 7: Co-operatives, Unions, Democracy, where she characterises co-operative/market socialism as "an attack made on the twigs of the capitalist tree" and states that "the law of wages is not shattered but applied by trade-union activity", which makes sense if you've read Marx or others who explained his ideas about wages.<br /><br />Ultimately it might be worth a read if you've already got some Marxist texts under your belt, if nothing else than to get some pleasure out of Luxemburg owning a guy who presented "not a single idea that was not refuted, crushed, reduced into dust by Marxism several decades ago".</span>
  <a data-text-id="259480037823087897" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
